# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-61508
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] A safety system (often called a safety-related system) consists of one or more safety functions.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety is intrinsically end-to-end in scope in that it has to treat the function of a component or subsystem as part of the function of the entire automatic protection function of any system.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Thus, although functional safety standards focus on electrical, electronic, and programmable systems (E/E/PS), the end-to-end scope means that in practice, functional safety methods must extend to the non-E/E/PS parts of the system that the E/E/PS actuators, valves, motor controls or monitors.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety is achieved when every specified safety function is carried out and the level of performance required of each safety function is met.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Assessment of the risk-reduction required by the safety function, which will involve a safety integrity level (SIL) or performance level or other quantification assessment.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] A SIL (or PL, AgPL, ASIL) applies to an end-to-end safety function of the safety-related system, not just to a component or a part of the system.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Ensuring the safety function performs to the design intent, including under conditions of incorrect operator input and failure modes.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] This will involve having the design and lifecycle managed by qualified and competent engineers carrying out processes to a recognized functional safety standard.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] In Europe, that standard is IEC EN 61508, or one of the industry specific standards derived from IEC EN 61508, or for simple systems some other standard like ISO 13849.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Verification that the system meets the assigned SIL, ASIL, PL or agPL by determining the probability of dangerous failure, checking minimum levels of redundancy, and reviewing systematic capability (SC).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] These three metrics have been called "the three barriers".
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Failure modes of a device are typically determined by failure mode and effects analysis of the system (FMEA).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Failure probabilities for each failure mode are typically determined using failure mode, effects, and diagnostic analysis FMEDA.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Conduct functional safety audits to examine and assess the evidence that the appropriate safety lifecycle management techniques were applied consistently and thoroughly in the relevant lifecycle stages of product.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Neither safety nor functional safety can be determined without considering the system as a whole and the environment with which it interacts.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety is inherently end-to-end in scope.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Modern systems often have software intensively commanding and controlling safety-critical functions.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Therefore, software functionality and correct software behavior must be part of the Functional safety engineering effort to ensure acceptable safety risk at the system level.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Any claim of functional safety for a component, subsystem or system should be independently certified to one of the recognized functional safety standards.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] A certified product can then be claimed to be functionally safe to a particular safety integrity level or a performance level in a specific range of applications: the certificate and the assessment report is provided to the customers describing the scope and limits of performance.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety is a technically challenging field.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Certifications should be done by independent organizations with experience and strong technical depth (electronics, programmable electronics, mechanical, and probabilistic analysis).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety certification is performed by accredited certification bodies (CB).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Accreditation is awarded to a CB organization by an accreditation body (AB).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] In the United States, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) is the AB for functional safety accreditation.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] In the United Kingdom, the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) provides functional safety accreditation.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] ABs are members of the International Accreditation Forum (IAF) for work in management systems, products, services, and personnel accreditation or the International Laboratory Accreditation Cooperation (ILAC) for laboratory testing accreditation.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] A multilateral recognition arrangement (MLA) between ABs will ensure global recognition of accredited CBs.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] IEC 61508 functional safety certification programs have been established by several global Certification Bodies.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Each has defined their own scheme based upon IEC 61508 and other functional safety standards.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The scheme lists the referenced standards and specifies procedures which describes their test methods, surveillance audit policy, public documentation policies, and other specific aspects of their program.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety certification programs for IEC 61508 standards are being offered globally by several recognized CBs including Intertek, SGS, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] An important element of functional safety certification is on-going surveillance by the certification agency.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Most CB organizations have included surveillance audits in their scheme.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The follow-up surveillance ensures that the product, sub-system, or system is still being manufactured in accordance with what was originally certified for functional safety.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Follow-up surveillance may occur at various frequencies depending on the certification body, but will typically look at the product's field failure history, hardware design changes, software changes, as well as the manufacturer's ongoing compliance of functional safety management systems.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] For military aerospace and defense systems MIL-STD-882E addresses functional hazard analyses (FHA) and determining which functions implemented in hardware and software are safety significant.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The Functional safety focus is on ensuring safety critical functions and functional threads in the system, subsystem and software are analyzed and verified for correct behavior per safety requirements, including functional failure conditions and faults and appropriate mitigation in the design.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] These system safety principles underpinning functional safety were developed in the military, nuclear and aerospace industries, and then taken up by rail transport, process and control industries developing sector specific standards.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety standards are applied across all industry sectors dealing with safety critical requirements and are especially applicable anytime software commands, controls or monitors a safety-critical function.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Thousands of products and processes meet the standards based on IEC 61508: from bathroom showers, automotive safety products, sensors, actuators, diving equipment, Process Controllers and their integration to ships, aircraft and major plants.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The US FAA have similar functional safety certification processes, in the form of ARP4761, US RTCA DO-178C for software and DO-254 for complex electronic hardware, which is applied throughout the aerospace industry.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety and design assurance on civil/commercial transport aircraft is documented in SAE ARP4754A as functional design assurance levels (FDALS).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The system FDALs drive the depth of engineering safety analysis.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The level of rigor (LOR) or safety tasks performed to ensure acceptable risk are dependent upon the identification of specific functional failure condition and hazard severity relating to the safety-critical functions (SCF).
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] In many cases functional behavior in embedded software is thoroughly analyzed and tested to ensure the system functions as intended under credible fault and failure conditions.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Functional safety is becoming the normal focused approach on complex software intensive systems and highly integrated systems with safety consequences.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The traditional software safety tasks and model based functional safety tasks are performed to provide objective safety evidence that the system functionality and safety features perform as intended in normal and off nominal failures.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The entry point of functional safety begins early in the process by performing Functional Hazard Analyses (FHA)to identify hazards and risks and to influence the safety design requirements and functional allocation and decomposition to mitigate hazards.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The behavior of the software and SCFs at the system level is a vital part of any functional safety effort.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Analyses and implementation results are documented in functional hazard assessments (FHA) or system safety assessments or safety cases.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Model-based functional safety processes are often used and required on highly integrated and complex software intensive systems to understand all of the many interactions and predicted behavior and to help in the safety verification and certification process.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] At Boeing, a Safety Review Board (SRB) is responsible for deciding only if an issue is or is not a safety issue.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] An SRB brings together multiple company subject-matter experts (SMEs) in many disciplines.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The most knowledgeable SME presents the issue, assisted and guided by the Aviation Safety organization.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] Any vote for "safety" results in a board decision of "safety".
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] In the US, NASA developed an infrastructure for safety critical systems adopted widely by industry, both in North America and elsewhere, with a standard, supported by guidelines.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The NASA standard and guidelines are built on ISO 12207, which is a software practice standard rather than a safety critical standard, hence the extensive nature of the documentation NASA has been obliged to add, compared to using a purpose designed standard such as IEC EN 61508.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] A certification process for systems developed in accord with the NASA guidelines exists.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The automotive industry has developed ISO 26262 "Road Vehicles Functional Safety Standard" based on IEC 61508.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The certification of those systems ensures the compliance with the relevant regulations and helps to protect the public.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The ATEX Directive has also adopted a functional safety standard, it is BS EN 50495:2010 "Safety Devices Required for the Safe Functioning of Equipment with Respect to Explosion Risks" covers safety related devices such as purge controllers and Ex e motor circuit breakers.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] It is applied by notified bodies under the ATEX Directive.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The standard ISO 26262 particularly addresses the automotive development cycle.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] It is a multi-part standard defining requirements and providing guidelines for achieving functional safety in E/E systems installed in series production passenger cars.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] ISO 26262 is considered a best-practice framework for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The compliance process usually takes time as employees need to be trained in order to develop the expected competencies.
[src:iec-61508/functional-safety] The standard ISO 26262 is considered a best practice framework for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] A **hazard analysis** is one of many methods that may be used to assess risk.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] At its core, the process entails describing a system object (such as a person or machine) that intends to conduct some activity.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] During the performance of that activity, an adverse event (referred to as a “factor”) may be encountered that could cause or contribute to an occurrence (mishap, incident, accident).
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] Finally, that occurrence will result in some outcome that may be measured in terms of the degree of loss or harm.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] This outcome may be measured on a continuous scale, such as an amount of monetary loss, or the outcomes may be categorized into various levels of severity e.g. environmental damage, personal injury, or reputational damage etc.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] The first step in hazard analysis is to identify the hazards.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] If an automobile is an object performing an activity such as driving over a bridge, and that bridge may become icy, then an icy bridge might be identified as a hazard.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] If this hazard is encountered, it could cause or contribute to the occurrence of an automobile accident, and the outcome of that occurrence could range in severity from a minor fender-bender to a fatal accident.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] A hazard analysis may be used to inform decisions regarding the mitigation of risk.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] For instance, the probability of encountering an icy bridge may be reduced by adding salt such that the ice will melt.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] Or, risk mitigation strategies may target the occurrence.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] For instance, putting tire chains on a vehicle does nothing to change the probability of a bridge becoming icy, but if an icy bridge is encountered, it does improve traction, reducing the chance of a sliding into another vehicle.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] Finally, risk may be managed by influencing the severity of outcomes.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] For instance, seatbelts and airbags do nothing to prevent bridges from becoming icy, nor do they prevent accidents caused by that ice.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] However, in the event of an accident, these devices lower the probability of the accident resulting in fatal or serious injuries.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] IEEE STD-1228-1994 Software Safety Plans prescribes industry best practices for conducting software safety hazard analyses to help ensure safety requirements and attributes are defined and specified for inclusion in software that commands, controls or monitors critical functions.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] When software is involved in a system, the development and design assurance of that software is often governed by DO-178C.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] The severity of consequence identified by the hazard analysis establishes the criticality level of the software.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] Software criticality levels range from A to E, corresponding to the severity of Catastrophic to No Safety Effect.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] Higher levels of rigor are required for level A and B software and corresponding functional tasks and work products is the system safety domain are used as objective evidence of meeting safety criteria and requirements.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] In 2009 a leading edge commercial standard was promulgated based on decades of proven system safety processes in DoD and NASA.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] ANSI/GEIA-STD-0010-2009 (Standard Best Practices for System Safety Program Development and Execution) is a demilitarized commercial best practice that uses proven holistic, comprehensive and tailored approaches for hazard prevention, elimination and control.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] It is centered around the hazard analysis and functional based safety process.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] When used as part of an aviation hazard analysis, "Severity" describes the outcome (the degree of loss or harm) that results from an occurrence (an aircraft accident or incident).
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] When categorized, severity categories must be mutually exclusive such that every occurrence has one, and only one, severity category associated with it.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] The definitions must also be collectively exhaustive such that all occurrences fall into one of the categories.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] In the US, the FAA includes five severity categories as part of its safety risk management policy.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] When used as part of an aviation hazard analysis, a "Likelihood" is a specific probability.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] It is the joint probability of a hazard occurring, that hazard causing or contributing to an aircraft accident or incident, and the resulting degree of loss or harm falling within one of the defined severity categories.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] Thus, if there are five severity categories, each hazard will have five likelihoods.
[src:iec-61508/hazard-analysis] In the US, the FAA provides a continuous probability scale for measuring likelihood, but also includes seven likelihood categories as part of its safety risk management policy.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61508 is a basic functional safety standard applicable to all industries.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] A probabilistic failure approach to account for the safety impact of device failures.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] All phases are concerned with the safety function of the system.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Central to the standard are the concepts of probabilistic risk for each safety function.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The risk is a function of frequency (or likelihood) of the hazardous event and the event consequence severity.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The risk is reduced to a tolerable level by applying safety functions which may consist of E/E/PES, associated mechanical devices, or other technologies.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Many requirements apply to all technologies but there is strong emphasis on programmable electronics especially in Part 3.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Specific techniques ensure that mistakes and errors are avoided across the entire life-cycle.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Errors introduced anywhere from the initial concept, risk analysis, specification, design, installation, maintenance and through to disposal could undermine even the most reliable protection.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61508 specifies techniques that should be used for each phase of the life-cycle.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The seven parts of the first edition of IEC 61508 were published in 1998 and 2000.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The second edition was published in 2010.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The standard requires that hazard and risk assessment be carried out for bespoke systems: 'The EUC (equipment under control) risk shall be evaluated, or estimated, for each determined hazardous event'.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The standard advises that 'Either qualitative or quantitative hazard and risk analysis techniques may be used' and offers guidance on a number of approaches.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] One of these, for the qualitative analysis of hazards, is a framework based on 6 categories of likelihood of occurrence and 4 of consequence.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The safety integrity level (SIL) provides a target to attain for each safety function.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] A risk assessment effort yields a target SIL for each safety function.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Architecture Constraints which are minimum levels of safety redundancy presented via two alternative methods - Route 1h and Route 2h.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Note the difference between function and system.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The system implementing the function might be in operation frequently (like an ECU for deploying an air-bag), but the function (like air-bag deployment) might be in demand intermittently.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Certification is third party attestation that a product, process, or system meets all requirements of the certification program.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Those requirements are listed in a document called the certification scheme.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61508 certification programs are operated by impartial third party organizations called *certification bodies* (CB).
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] These CBs are accredited to operate following other international standards including ISO/IEC 17065 and ISO/IEC 17025.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Certification bodies are accredited to perform the auditing, assessment, and testing work by an *accreditation body* (AB).
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] There is often one national AB in each country.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] These ABs operate per the requirements of ISO/IEC 17011, a standard that contains requirements for the competence, consistency, and impartiality of accreditation bodies when accrediting conformity assessment bodies.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] ABs are members of the International Accreditation Forum (IAF) for work in management systems, products, services, and personnel accreditation or the International Laboratory Accreditation Cooperation (ILAC) for laboratory accreditation.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61508 certification programs have been established by several global Certification Bodies.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61508 certification programs are being offered globally by several recognized CBs including exida, Intertek, SGS-TÜV Saar, TÜV Nord, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] ISO 26262 is an adaptation of IEC 61508 for Automotive Electric/Electronic Systems.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] It is being widely adopted by the major car manufacturers.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Before the launch of ISO 26262, the development of software for safety related automotive systems was predominantly covered by the Motor Industry Software Reliability Association (MISRA) guidelines.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The MISRA project was conceived to develop guidelines for the creation of embedded software in road vehicle electronic systems.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] A set of guidelines for the development of vehicle based software was published in November 1994.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] This document provided the first automotive industry interpretation of the principles of the, then emerging, IEC 61508 standard.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Today MISRA is most widely known for its guidelines on how to use the C and C++ languages.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] MISRA C has gone on to become the de facto standard for embedded C programming in the majority of safety-related industries, and is also used to improve software quality even where safety is not the main consideration.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 62279 provides a specific interpretation of IEC 61508 for railway applications.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] It is intended to cover the development of software for railway control and protection including communications, signalling and processing systems.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] EN 50128 and EN 50657 are equivalent CENELEC standards of IEC 62279.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The process industry sector includes many types of manufacturing processes, such as refineries, petrochemical, chemical, pharmaceutical, pulp and paper, and power.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61511 is a technical standard which sets out practices in the engineering of systems that ensure the safety of an industrial process through the use of instrumentation.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 61513 provides requirements and recommendations for the instrumentation and control for systems important to safety of nuclear power plants.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] It indicates the general requirements for systems that contain conventional hardwired equipment, computer-based equipment or a combination of both types of equipment.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] An overview list of safety norms specific for nuclear power plants is published by ISO.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] IEC 62061 is the machinery-specific implementation of IEC 61508.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] It provides requirements that are applicable to the system level design of all types of machinery safety-related electrical control systems and also for the design of non-complex subsystems or devices.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] Software written in accordance with IEC 61508 may need to be unit tested, depending up on the SIL it needs to achieve.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] The main requirement in Unit Testing is to ensure that the software is fully tested at the function level and that all possible branches and paths are taken through the software.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] In some higher SIL level applications, the software code coverage requirement is much tougher and an MC/DC code coverage criterion is used rather than simple branch coverage.
[src:iec-61508/iec-61508] To obtain the MC/DC (modified condition/decision coverage) coverage information, one will need a Unit Testing tool, sometimes referred to as a Software Module Testing tool.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:iec-61508/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] In functional safety, a **safety instrumented system** (**SIS**) is an engineered set of hardware and software controls which provides a protection layer that shuts down a chemical, nuclear, electrical, or mechanical system, or part of it, if a hazardous condition is detected.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] It relates to the prevention of major accidents, and not occupational safety issues.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] An SIS contains one or more **safety instrumented functions (SIF)**.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The SIS is credited with a certain measure of reliability depending on its **safety integrity level** **(SIL)**.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The required SIL is determined from a quantitative process hazard analysis (PHA), such as a Layers of Protection Analysis (LOPA).
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The SIL requirements are verified during the design, construction, installation, and operation of the SIS.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The required functionality may be verified by design reviews, factory acceptance testing, site acceptance testing, and regular functional testing.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The PHA is in turn based on a hazard identification exercise.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] In the process industries (oil and gas production, refineries, chemical plants, etc.), this exercise is usually a hazard and operability study (HAZOP).
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The HAZOP usually identifies not only the process hazards of a plant (such as release of hazardous materials due to the process operating outside the safe limits of the plant) but also the SIFs protecting the plant from such excursions.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] An SIS is intended to perform specific control functions to prevent unsafe process operations when unacceptable or dangerous conditions occur.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] Because of its criticality, safety instrumented systems must be independent from all other control systems that control the same equipment, in order to ensure SIS functionality is not compromised.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] A SIS is composed of the same types of control elements (including sensors, logic solvers, actuators and other control equipment) as a Basic Process Control System (BPCS).
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] However, all of the control elements in an SIS are dedicated solely to the proper functioning of the SIS.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] All these components must function properly for the SIS to perform its SIF.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The logic solver may use electrical, electronic or programmable electronic equipment, such as relays, trip amplifiers, or programmable logic controllers.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] Support systems, such as power, instrument air, and communications, are generally required for SIS operation.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The support systems should be designed to provide the required integrity and reliability.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] SIFs are implemented as part of an overall risk reduction strategy which is intended to minimize the likelihood of a previously identified accident that could range from minor equipment damage up to the uncontrolled catastrophic release of energy or materials.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] The safe state must be achieved in a sufficiently short amount of time (known as *process safety time*) to prevent the accident.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] International standard IEC 61511 was published in 2003 to provide guidance to end-users on the application of Safety Instrumented Systems in the process industries.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] This standard is based on IEC 61508, a generic standard for functional safety that includes aspects on design, construction, and operation of electrical/electronic/programmable electronic systems.
[src:iec-61508/safety-instrumented-system] Other industry sectors may also have standards that are based on IEC 61508, such as IEC 62061 (machinery systems), IEC 62425 (for railway signaling systems), IEC 61513 (for nuclear systems), and ISO 26262 (for road vehicles).
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] In functional safety, **safety integrity level** (**SIL**) is defined as the relative level of risk-reduction provided by a safety instrumented function (SIF), i.e. the measurement of the performance required of the SIF.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] In the functional safety standards based on the IEC 61508 standard, four SILs are defined, with SIL4 being the most dependable and SIL1 the least.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The applicable SIL is determined based on a number of quantitative factors in combination with qualitative factors, such as risk assessments and safety lifecycle management.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Other standards, however, may have different SIL number definitions.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Assignment, or allocation of SIL is an exercise in risk analysis where the risk associated with a specific hazard, which is intended to be protected against by a SIF, is calculated without the beneficial risk reduction effect of the SIF.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] That unmitigated risk is then compared against a tolerable risk target.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The difference between the unmitigated risk and the tolerable risk, if the unmitigated risk is higher than tolerable, must be addressed through risk reduction of provided by the SIF.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] This amount of required risk reduction is correlated with the SIL target.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] In essence, each order of magnitude of risk reduction that is required correlates with an increase in SIL, up to a maximum of SIL4.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Should the risk assessment establish that the required SIL cannot be achieved by a SIL4 SIF, then alternative arrangements must be designed, such as non-instrumented safeguards (e.g, a pressure relief valve).
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] There are several methods used to assign a SIL.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Of the methods presented above, LOPA is by far the most commonly used in large industrial facilities, such as for example chemical process plants.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The assignment may be tested using both pragmatic and controllability approaches, applying industry guidance such as the one published by the UK HSE.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] SIL assignment processes that use the HSE guidance to ratify assignments developed from risk matrices have been certified to meet IEC 61508.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] There are several problems inherent in the use of safety integrity levels.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] According to IEC 61508, the SIL concept must be related to the dangerous failure rate of a system, not just its failure rate or the failure rate of a component part, such as the software.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Definition of the dangerous failure modes by safety analysis is intrinsic to the proper determination of the failure rate.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The International Electrotechnical Commission's (IEC) standard IEC 61508 defines SIL using requirements grouped into two broad categories: *hardware safety integrity* and *systematic safety integrity*.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] A device or system must meet the requirements for *both* categories to achieve a given SIL.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The SIL requirements for hardware safety integrity are based on a probabilistic analysis of the device.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] In order to achieve a given SIL, the device must meet targets for the maximum probability of dangerous failure and a minimum safe failure fraction.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The concept of 'dangerous failure' must be rigorously defined for the system in question, normally in the form of requirement constraints whose integrity is verified throughout system development.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The actual targets required vary depending on the likelihood of a demand, the complexity of the device(s), and types of redundancy used.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Hazards of a control system must be identified then analysed through risk analysis.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Mitigation of these risks continues until their overall contribution to the hazard are considered acceptable.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The tolerable level of these risks is specified as a safety requirement in the form of a target 'probability of a dangerous failure' in a given period of time, stated as a discrete SIL.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Certification schemes, such as the CASS Scheme (Conformity Assessment of Safety-related Systems) are used to establish whether a device meets a particular SIL.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Third parties that can provide certification include Bureau Veritas, CSA Group, TÜV Rheinland, TÜV SÜD and UL among others.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The requirements of these schemes can be met either by establishing a rigorous development process, or by establishing that the device has sufficient operating history to argue that it has been proven in use.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] Electric and electronic devices can be certified for use in functional safety applications according to IEC 61508.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] There are a number of application-specific standards based on or adapted from IEC 61508, such as IEC 61511 for the process industry sector.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] This standard is used in the petrochemical and hazardous chemical industries, among others.
[src:iec-61508/safety-integrity-level] The following standards use SIL as a measure of reliability and/or risk reduction.
